with $P_{A}=I_{n}-A^{\top}\left(A A^{\top}\right)^{\dagger} A$. We conclude that the asymptotic expansion

$$
\sqrt{t}\left(\beta^{\gamma}-\beta^{*}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}} \sum_{r=1}^{t} D_{\beta}\left(\theta^{*}\right)+o_{p}(1)
$$

holds, where

$$
D_{\beta}(\theta)=-(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H})^{\dagger}\left(\mu^{*}-\bar{\mu}^{*}\right)
$$

and that the asymptotic distribution of $\sqrt{t}\left(\beta^{\gamma}-\beta^{*}\right)$ is $\mathcal{N}\left(0, \Sigma_{\beta}\right)$ with $\Sigma_{\beta}=\mathbb{E}\left[D_{\beta} D_{\beta}^{\top}\right]$. Note $\mathbb{E}\left[D_{\beta}\right]=0$.
Proof of $\beta^{\gamma} \xrightarrow{\theta} \beta^{*}$. This follows from Lemma EC. 12 .

Proof of Asymptotic Distribution for pacing multiplier $\beta$. This follows from the above discussion.
Proof of Asymptotic Distribution for revenue REV. We use a stochastic equicontinuity argument. Given the item sequence $\gamma=\left(\theta^{1}, \theta^{2} \ldots\right)$, define the (random) operator

$$
\nu_{t} g=\sqrt{t}\left(P_{t}-P\right) g=\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t}\left(g\left(\theta^{\tau}\right)-\mathbb{E}[g]\right)
$$

where $g: \Theta \rightarrow \mathbb{R}, \mathbb{E}[g]=\int g s \mathrm{~d} \theta$. Note $p^{*}(\theta)=\max _{i} \beta_{i}^{*} v_{i}(\theta)=f\left(\theta, \beta^{*}\right), \mathrm{REV}^{*}=P f\left(\cdot, \beta^{*}\right), p^{\tau}=f\left(\theta^{\tau}, \beta^{\gamma}\right)$ and $\mathrm{REV}^{\gamma}=P_{t} f\left(\cdot, \beta^{\gamma}\right)$ we obtain the decomposition

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sqrt{t}\left(\mathrm{REV}^{\gamma}-\mathrm{REV}^{*}\right)=\underbrace{\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t}\left(f\left(\theta^{\tau}, \beta^{*}\right)-\bar{f}\left(\beta^{*}\right)\right)}_{=\cdot \mathrm{I}_{t}}+\underbrace{\nu_{t}\left(f\left(\cdot, \beta^{\gamma}\right)-f\left(\cdot, \beta^{*}\right)\right)}_{=\cdot \mathrm{II}_{t}} \\
& +\underbrace{\sqrt{t}\left(\bar{f}\left(\beta^{\gamma}\right)-\bar{f}\left(\beta^{*}\right)\right)}_{=\cdot \mathrm{III}_{t}}
\end{aligned}
$$

For the term $\mathrm{I}_{t}$, it can be written as $\mathrm{I}_{t}=\nu_{t}\left(p^{*}(\cdot)-\mathrm{REV}^{*}\right)$. By the linear representation for $\beta^{\gamma}-\beta^{*}$ in Eq. (EC.39), applying the delta method, we get the linear representation result

$$
\mathrm{III}_{t}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t} \nabla \bar{f}\left(\beta^{*}\right)^{\top} D_{\beta}\left(\theta^{*}\right)+o_{p}(1)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t}\left(\bar{\mu}^{*}\right)^{\top} D_{\beta}\left(\theta^{\tau}\right)+o_{p}(1)
$$

We will show $\mathrm{II}_{t}=o_{p}(1)$. The difficulty lies in that the operator $\nu_{t}$ and the pacing multiplier $\beta^{\gamma}$ depend on the same batch of items. This can be handled with the stochastic equicontinuity argument. The desired claim $\mathrm{II}_{t}=o_{p}(1)$ follows by verifying that the function class $\mathcal{F}_{1}=\{\theta \mapsto f(\cdot, \beta): \beta \in B\}$ (same as that defined in Lemma EC.22) is VC-subgraph and Donsker. This is true by Lemma EC.22. By Lemma EC. 14 we know for any $\delta_{t} \downarrow 0$,

$$
\sup _{w \in\left[\delta_{t}\right]_{L^{2}}} \nu_{t}\left(f(\cdot, w)-f\left(\cdot, \beta^{*}\right)\right)=o_{p}(1)
$$

where $\left[\delta_{t}\right]_{L^{2}}=\left\{\beta: \beta \in B, \int\left(f(\cdot, \beta)-f\left(\cdot, \beta^{*}\right)\right)^{2} s \mathrm{~d} \theta \leq \delta_{t}\right\}$. Noting that for all $\beta, w, \theta$, it holds $\mid f(\theta, \beta)-$ $f(\theta, w)|\leq \bar{v}| \beta-w|_{\infty}$, we know that $\int\left[f(\cdot, \beta)-f\left(\cdot, \beta^{*}\right)\right]^{2} s \mathrm{~d} \theta \rightarrow 0$ as $\beta \rightarrow \beta^{*}$. Then by Lemma EC.20, we know Eq. (EC.40) holds with $\left[\delta_{t}\right]_{L^{2}}$ replaced with $\left[\delta_{t}\right]=\left\{\beta: \beta \in B,\left\|\beta-\beta^{*}\right\|_{2} \leq \delta_{t}\right\}$. Combined with the fact that $\beta^{\gamma} \xrightarrow{\theta} \beta^{*}$, by Lemma EC. 21 we know $\mathrm{II}_{t}=o_{p}(1)$.

To summarize, we obtain the linear expansion

$$
\sqrt{t}\left(\mathrm{REV}^{\gamma}-\mathrm{REV}^{*}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t}\left(p^{*}\left(\theta^{\tau}\right)-\mathrm{REV}^{*}+\left(\bar{\mu}^{*}\right)^{\top} D_{\beta}\left(\theta^{\tau}\right)\right)+o_{p}(1)
$$

Let $D_{\mathrm{REV}}(\theta)=p^{*}\left(\theta^{\tau}\right)-\mathrm{REV}^{*}+\left(\bar{\mu}^{*}\right)^{\top} D_{\beta}\left(\theta^{\tau}\right)$.
We complete the proof of Theorem 10. Q.E.D.

# G.4. Proof of Corollary 3 

Proof of Corollary 3 For $i$ such that $\beta_{i}^{*}=1$, we know $\beta_{i}^{\gamma}-1=o_{p}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}}\right)$ holds. Then $\mathbb{P}\left(\beta_{i}^{\gamma}<1-\varepsilon_{t}\right)=$ $\mathbb{P}\left(o_{p}(1)>\sqrt{t} \varepsilon_{t}\right) \rightarrow 0$, using the smoothing rate condition $\sqrt{t} \varepsilon_{t} \rightarrow c \in(0, \infty]$. For $i$ such that $\beta_{i}^{*}<1$, we know $\beta^{\gamma}-\beta_{i}^{*}=o_{p}(1)$ by consistency of $\beta^{\gamma}$. Then $\mathbb{P}\left(\beta_{i}^{\gamma}<1-\varepsilon_{t}\right)=\mathbb{P}\left(o_{p}(1)<\left(1-\beta_{i}^{*}\right)-\varepsilon_{t}\right) \rightarrow 1$ by $\varepsilon_{t}=o(1)$ and $1-\beta_{i}^{*}>0 . \quad$ Q.E.D.

# G.5. Proof of Normality of NSW, $u$, and $\delta$ in FPPE 

We define NSW and utility in limit FPPE. We use (.)* to denote limit FPPE quantities. Given an FPPE $\left(\beta^{*}, p^{*}\right)$, we define by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \delta_{i}^{*}=b_{i}-\int p^{*} s x_{i}^{*} \mathrm{~d} \theta, \quad \bar{\mu}_{i}^{*}=\int v_{i} s x_{i}^{*} \mathrm{~d} \theta \\
& u_{i}^{*}=\bar{\mu}_{i}^{*}+\delta_{i}^{*}
\end{aligned}
$$

the leftover budget, the item utility and the total utility of buyer $i$. Let $\delta^{*}, \bar{\mu}^{*}, u^{*}$ be the vectors that collect these quantities for all buyers. In FPPE it holds that

$$
u_{i}^{*}=b_{i} / \beta_{i}^{*}
$$

We next define these quantities in finite FPPE. To emphasize dependence on the item sequence $\gamma$, we use $(.)^{\gamma}$ to denote equilibrium quantities in $\widehat{\text { FPPE }}(b, v, 1 / t, \gamma)$. We let $\left(\beta^{\gamma}, p^{\gamma}\right)$ be an observed FPPE with $x^{\gamma}=\left(x_{1}^{\gamma}, \ldots\right)$. The leftover budget $\delta_{i}^{*}=b_{i}-\sigma \sum_{\tau} p^{\tau} x_{i}^{\gamma, \tau}$, item utility $\bar{\mu}_{i}=\sigma \sum_{\tau=1}^{t} v_{i}^{\tau} x_{i}^{\gamma, \tau}$ and total utility $u_{i}^{\gamma}=\delta_{i}^{\gamma}+\bar{\mu}_{i}$ are defined similarly. Let $\delta^{\gamma}, \bar{\mu}, u^{\gamma}$ be the vectors that collect these quantities for all buyers. The observed revenue is $\mathrm{REV}^{\gamma}=\sigma \sum_{\tau=1}^{t} p^{\tau}$, and NSW is $\mathrm{NSW}^{\gamma}=\sum_{i=1}^{n} b_{i} \log u_{i}^{\gamma}$.

Corollary EC.1. Under the same conditions as Theorem $10, \sqrt{t}\left(u^{\gamma}-u^{*}\right), \sqrt{t}\left(\delta^{\gamma}-\delta^{*}\right)$ and $\sqrt{t}\left(\mathrm{NSW}^{\gamma}-\right.$ $\left.\mathrm{NSW}^{*}\right)$ are asymptotically normal with (co)variances $\Sigma_{n}=\operatorname{diag}\left(b_{i} /\left(\beta_{i}^{*}\right)^{2}\right) \Sigma_{\beta} \operatorname{diag}\left(b_{i} /\left(\beta_{i}^{*}\right)^{2}\right), \quad \Sigma_{\delta}=\left(I_{n}-\right.$ $\left.\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right) \Omega\left(I_{n}-\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right)^{\top}$, and $\sigma_{\mathrm{NSW}}^{2}=\operatorname{Vec}\left(b_{i} / \beta_{i}^{*}\right)^{\top} \Sigma_{\beta} \operatorname{Vec}\left(b_{i} / \beta_{i}^{*}\right)$, respectively.

Proof of Corollary EC. 1 Proof of Asymptotic Distribution for individual utility $u$. We use the delta method; see Theorem 3.1 from Van der Vaart (2000). Note $u^{*}=g\left(\beta^{*}\right)$ with $g: \mathbb{R}^{n} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{n}, g(\beta)=$ $\left[b_{1} / \beta_{1}, \ldots, b_{n} / \beta_{n}\right]^{\top}$. By Eq. (EC.39), it holds

$$
\sqrt{t}\left(u^{\gamma}-u^{*}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t} \nabla g\left(\beta^{*}\right) D_{\beta}\left(\theta^{\tau}\right)+o_{p}(1)
$$

Finally, noting $\nabla g\left(\beta^{*}\right)=\operatorname{diag}\left(-b_{i} /\left(\beta_{i}^{*}\right)^{2}\right)$ we complete the proof.
Proof of Asymptotic Distribution for Nash social welfare NSW. We use the delta method. Note NSW* $=$ $g\left(\beta^{*}\right)$ with $g: \mathbb{R}^{n} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}, g(\beta)=\sum_{i=1}^{n} b_{i} \log \left(b_{i} / \beta_{i}\right)$. By Eq. (EC.39) it holds

$$
\sqrt{t}\left(\mathrm{NSW}^{\gamma}-\mathrm{NSW}^{*}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t} \nabla g\left(\beta^{*}\right)^{\top} D_{\beta}\left(\theta^{\tau}\right)+o_{p}(1)
$$

Finally, noting $\nabla g\left(\beta^{*}\right)=\operatorname{Vec}\left(b_{i} / \beta_{i}^{*}\right)$.
Proof of Asymptotic Distribution for leftover budget $\delta$. This is a direct consequence of Theorem 4.1 in Shapiro (1989). By that theorem, it holds that

$$
\sqrt{t}\left[\frac{\beta^{\gamma}-\beta^{*}}{\delta_{I_{=}}^{\gamma}-\delta_{I=}^{*}}\right] \xrightarrow{d} \mathcal{N}\left(0, \Sigma_{\text {joint }}\right)
$$

with

$$
\Sigma_{\text {joint }}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\mathcal{H} & A^{\top} \\
A & 0
\end{array}\right]^{-1}\left[\begin{array}{ll}
\Omega & 0 \\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\mathcal{H} & A^{\top} \\
A & 0
\end{array}\right]^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger} \Omega\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger} & \left[Q \Omega\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right]^{\top} \\
Q \Omega\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger} & Q \Omega Q^{\top}
\end{array}\right]
$$

where $A \in \mathbb{R}^{|I_{\infty}| \times n}$ whose rows are $\left\{e_{i}^{\top}, i \in I_{\infty}\right\}, Q=\left(A \mathcal{H}^{-1} A^{\top}\right)^{-1} A \mathcal{H}^{-1} \in \mathbb{R}^{|I_{\infty}| \times n}$ and $\Omega=\operatorname{Cov}\left(\mu^{*}\right)$. By a matrix equality, noting matrix $A$ 's rows are distinct basis vectors, it holds

$$
\left(A \mathcal{H}^{-1} A^{\top}\right)^{-1} A \mathcal{H}^{-1}=A\left(I_{n}-\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right)
$$

Moreover, for other entries of $\delta^{\gamma}$, i.e., $\delta_{I_{<}}^{\gamma}$, their asymptotic variance will be zero. The matrix $\left(I_{n}-\right.$ $\left.\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right) \Omega\left(I_{n}-\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right)^{\top}$ is zero at the $(i, j)$-th entry if $i$ or $j \in I_{<}$. Summarizing, the asymptotic variance of $\sqrt{t}\left(\delta^{\gamma}-\delta^{*}\right)$ is $\left(I_{n}-\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right) \Omega\left(I_{n}-\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right)^{\top}$.

An alternative proof is by the delta method and a stochastic equicontinuity argument. To summarize, it holds $\sqrt{t}\left(\delta^{\gamma}-\delta^{*}\right) \xrightarrow{d} \mathcal{N}\left(0,\left(I_{n}-\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right) \Omega\left(I_{n}-\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right)^{\top}\right)$ and the linear expansion

$$
\sqrt{t}\left(\delta^{\gamma}-\delta^{*}\right)=t^{-1 / 2} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t}\left(I_{n}-\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\right)\left(\mu^{*}\left(\theta^{\tau}\right)-\bar{\mu}^{*}\right)+o_{p}(1)
$$

holds. In the case where $I_{\infty}=\emptyset$, i.e., $\delta_{i}^{*}=0$ for all $i$, we have $\mathcal{H}_{B}=\mathcal{H}$ and so $I_{n}-\mathcal{H}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}=0$.
We complete the proof of Corollary EC. 1 Q.E.D.

# G.6. Proof of Fast Convergence of Pacing Multipliers 

Lemma EC.23. Let Assumption 1 and Assumption 2 hold. Then $\mathbb{P}\left(\beta_{i}^{\gamma}=1\right) \rightarrow 1$ for all $i \in I_{\infty}$, and $\mathbb{P}\left(\delta_{i}^{\gamma}=\right.$ $0) \rightarrow 1$ for all $i \in I_{<}$.

Proof of Lemma EC. 23 Eq. (EC.45) implies $\delta_{i}^{\gamma}-\delta_{i}^{*}=o_{p}(1)$ for all $i \in I_{\infty}$. Assumption 2 implies $\delta_{i}^{*}>0$ for all $i \in I_{\infty}$. Combining the two gives $\mathbb{P}\left(\delta_{i}^{\gamma}>0, \forall i \in I_{\infty}\right) \rightarrow 1$, which implies the desired claim by the strict complementarity between $\beta^{\gamma} \leq 1$ and $\delta^{\gamma} \geq 0$. The proof of $\mathbb{P}\left(\delta_{i}^{\gamma}=0\right) \rightarrow 1$ follows similarly. Q.E.D.

## G.7. Proof of Theorem 11

Proof of Theorem 11 According to the discussion in Section D.5, we calculate the derivative of the map $\alpha \mapsto \mathrm{REV}_{\alpha, g}^{*}$ at $\alpha=0$.

For a given perturbation $(\alpha, g)$, we let $p_{\alpha, g}^{*}$ and $\mathrm{REV}_{\alpha, g}^{*}$ be the limit FPPE price and revenue under supply distribution $s_{\alpha, g}$. Let $S_{\alpha, g}(\theta)=\nabla_{\alpha} \log s_{\alpha, g}(\theta)$ be the score function. So $\nabla_{\alpha} s_{\alpha, g}=s_{\alpha, g} S_{\alpha, g}$ and $\int S_{\alpha, g} s_{\alpha, g} \mathrm{~d} \theta=0$. Obviously with our parametrization of $s_{\alpha, g}$ we have $S_{0, g}(\theta)=g(\theta)$ by Eq. (13). We next find the derivative of $\alpha \mapsto \mathrm{REV}_{\alpha, g}^{*}$ at $\alpha=0$. Recall $f$ is defined as $f(\theta, \beta)=\max _{i} v_{i}(\theta) \beta_{i}$ and the price is produced by the highest bid, i.e., $p_{\alpha, g}^{*}(\theta)=\max _{i} \beta_{\alpha, g}^{*} v_{i}(\theta)=f\left(\theta, \beta_{\alpha, g}^{*}\right)$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \nabla_{\alpha} \mathrm{REV}_{\alpha, g}^{*}=\nabla_{\alpha} \int f\left(\theta, \beta_{\alpha, g}^{*}\right) s_{\alpha, g}(\theta) \mathrm{d} \theta \\
& =\int\left[\nabla_{\beta} f\left(\theta, \beta_{\alpha, g}^{*}\right) \nabla_{\alpha} \beta_{\alpha, g}^{*}+f\left(\theta, \beta_{\alpha, g}^{*}\right) S_{\alpha, g}(\theta)\right] s_{\alpha, g}(\theta) \mathrm{d} \theta
\end{aligned}
$$

Above we exchange the gradient and the expectation and then apply the chain rule. By a perturbation result by Lemma 8.1 and Prop. 1 from Duchi and Ruan (2021), under Assumption 1 and Assumption 2,

$$
\left.\nabla_{\alpha} \beta_{\alpha, g}^{*}\right|_{\alpha=0}=-\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger} \Sigma_{\mu^{*}, g}
$$

with $\Sigma_{\mu^{*}, g}=\mathbb{E}_{s}\left[\left(\mu^{*}(\theta)-\bar{\mu}^{*}\right) g(\theta)^{\top}\right]$. Plugging in $\mathbb{E}_{s}\left[\nabla_{\beta} f\left(\theta, \beta_{0, g}^{*}\right)\right]=\bar{\mu}^{*}, f\left(\theta, \beta_{0, g}^{*}\right)=p^{*}(\theta)$ and $S_{0, g}=g$, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left.\nabla_{\alpha} \mathrm{REV}_{\alpha, g}^{*}\right|_{\alpha=0} & =-\left(\bar{\mu}^{*}\right)^{\top}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger} \Sigma_{\mu^{*}, g}+\mathbb{E}_{s}\left[\left(p^{*}(\theta)-\mathrm{REV}^{*}\right) g(\theta)\right] \\
& =\mathbb{E}\left[\left(-\left(\bar{\mu}^{*}\right)^{\top}\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}\right)^{\dagger}\left(\mu^{*}(\theta)-\bar{\mu}^{*}\right)+\left(p^{*}(\theta)-\mathrm{REV}^{*}\right)\right) g(\theta)\right] \\
& =\mathbb{E}\left[D_{\mathrm{REV}}(\theta) g(\theta)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Now we have the two components required to invoke the local minimax result. Given a symmetric quasiconvex loss $L: \mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$, we recall the local asymptotic risk for any procedure $\left\{\hat{r}_{t}: \Theta^{t} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}\right\}$ that aims to estimate the revenue:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \operatorname{LAR}_{\mathrm{REV}}\left(\left\{\hat{r}_{t}\right\}\right)= \\
& \sup _{g \in G_{d}, d \in \mathbb{N}} \lim _{t \rightarrow \infty} \liminf _{\|\alpha\|_{2} \leq \frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{t}}} \mathbb{E}_{\sqrt{\hat{r}_{t}}}\left[L\left(\sqrt{t}\left(\hat{r}_{t}-\mathrm{REV}_{\alpha, g}^{*}\right)\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Following the argument in Duchi and Ruan (2021, Sec. 8.3) it holds

$$
\inf _{\left\{\hat{r}_{t}\right\}} \operatorname{LAR}_{\mathrm{REV}}\left(\left\{\hat{r}_{t}\right\}\right) \geq \mathbb{E}\left[L\left(\mathcal{N}\left(0, \mathbb{E}\left[D_{\mathrm{REV}}^{2}(\theta)\right]\right)\right)\right]
$$

We complete the proof of Theorem 11.
Q.E.D.

# G.8. Proof of Theorem 12 

Proof of Theorem 12 Proof of $\hat{\Sigma}_{\beta} \xrightarrow{p} \Sigma_{\beta}$. We first show $\hat{\mathcal{H}} \xrightarrow{p} \mathcal{H}$ by verifying conditions in Lemma EC.13. All conditions are easy to verify except the stochastic equicontinuity condition. By Lemma EC. 22 we know the SE condition holds. We conclude $\hat{\mathcal{H}} \xrightarrow{p} \mathcal{H}$. Next we show $\mathbb{P}(\hat{\mathcal{P}}=\mathcal{P}) \rightarrow 1$. This follows from Corollary 3. We conclude $\mathbb{P}(\hat{\mathcal{P}}=\mathcal{P}) \rightarrow 1$. For any $\epsilon>0, \mathbb{P}\left(\left\|(\hat{\mathcal{P}} \hat{\mathcal{H}} \hat{\mathcal{P}})^{\dagger}-(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H} \mathcal{P})^{\dagger}\right\|_{F}>\epsilon\right) \leq \mathbb{P}\left(\left\|(\hat{\mathcal{P}} \hat{\mathcal{H}} \hat{\mathcal{P}})^{\dagger}-(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H} \mathcal{P})^{\dagger}\right\|_{F}>\epsilon, \hat{\mathcal{P}}=\mathcal{P}\right)+\mathbb{P}(\hat{\mathcal{P}} \neq \mathcal{P})=$ $\mathbb{P}\left(\left\|\left[\hat{\mathcal{H}}_{<}\right]^{-1}-\left[\mathcal{H}_{<}\right]^{-1}\right\|_{F}>\epsilon\right)+\mathbb{P}(\hat{\mathcal{P}} \neq \mathcal{P}) \rightarrow 0$ by $\hat{\mathcal{H}} \xrightarrow{p} \mathcal{H}$. This follows by Lemma EC.6. We rewrite $\hat{\Sigma}_{\beta}$ as $\hat{\Sigma}_{\beta}=(\hat{\mathcal{P}} \hat{\mathcal{H}} \hat{\mathcal{P}})^{\dagger}\left(\frac{1}{t} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t}\left(\mu^{\tau}-\bar{\mu}\right)^{\oplus 2}\right)(\hat{\mathcal{P}} \hat{\mathcal{H}} \hat{\mathcal{P}})^{\dagger}$ which converges in probability to $(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H})^{\dagger} \operatorname{Cov}\left(\mu^{*}\right)(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H} \mathcal{P})^{\dagger}=\Sigma_{\beta}$.

Proof of $\hat{\sigma}_{\mathrm{REV}}^{2} \xrightarrow{p} \sigma_{\mathrm{REV}}^{2}$. We rewrite $\sigma_{\mathrm{REV}}^{2}=\underbrace{\mathbb{E}\left[\left(p^{*}-\mathrm{REV}^{*}\right)^{2}\right]}_{\hat{\Pi}_{t}}+\underbrace{\left(\bar{\mu}^{*}\right)^{\top}(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H})^{\dagger} \operatorname{Cov}\left(\mu^{*}\right)(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H} \mathcal{P})^{\dagger} \bar{\mu}^{*}}_{\hat{\Pi}_{t}}+$ $2 \mathbb{E}\left[\left(p^{*}-\mathrm{REV}^{*}\right)\left(\mu^{*}-\bar{\mu}^{*}\right)\right]^{\top}(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H} \mathcal{P})^{\dagger} \bar{\mu}^{*}$ and $\hat{\sigma}_{\mathrm{REV}}^{2}=\underbrace{\frac{1}{t} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t}\left(p^{\tau}-\mathrm{REV}^{\gamma}\right)^{2}}_{\hat{\Pi}_{t}}+\underbrace{\left(\bar{\mu}^{\gamma}\right)^{\top}(\hat{\mathcal{P}} \hat{\mathcal{H}} \hat{\mathcal{P}})^{\dagger} \hat{\Omega}(\hat{\mathcal{P}} \hat{\mathcal{H}} \hat{\mathcal{P}})^{\dagger} \bar{\mu}^{\gamma}}_{\hat{\Pi}_{t}}+$ $2 \underbrace{\left(\frac{1}{t} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t}\left(p^{\tau}-\mathrm{REV}^{\gamma}\right)\left(\mu^{\tau}-\bar{\mu}^{\gamma}\right)\right)^{\top}(\hat{\mathcal{P}} \hat{\mathcal{H}} \hat{\mathcal{P}})^{\dagger} \bar{\mu}^{\gamma}}_{\hat{\Pi}_{t}}$. We have $\hat{\mathrm{I}}_{t} \xrightarrow{\pi} \mathrm{I}_{t}$ by invoking Lemma EC.22, applying a uniform LLN and using the fact that $\beta^{\gamma} \xrightarrow{\pi} \beta^{*}$. And $\hat{\Pi}_{t} \xrightarrow{\pi} \mathrm{II}$ holds by $\bar{\mu} \xrightarrow{\pi} \bar{\mu}^{*},(\hat{\mathcal{P}} \hat{\mathcal{H}} \hat{\mathcal{P}})^{\dagger} \xrightarrow{\pi}(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H} \mathcal{P})^{\dagger}$ and $\hat{\Omega} \xrightarrow{\pi} \Omega$, and applying Slutsky's theorem. Finally, $\hat{\Pi I}_{t} \xrightarrow{\pi} \mathrm{III}$ by $\mathcal{F}_{1} \cdot \mathcal{F}_{2}$ is Donsker by Lemma EC. 19 and thus a uniform law of large number holds, and that $\beta^{\gamma} \xrightarrow{\pi} \beta^{*}$.

We complete the proof of Theorem 12. Q.E.D.

## G.9. Proof of Simplified Estimation Results

Proof of Theorem 13 First we show $D_{\mathrm{REV}}(\theta)=p^{*}(\theta)-\bar{\mu}^{* \top}(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H} \mathcal{P})^{\dagger} \mu^{*}(\theta)=\hat{p}^{*}(\theta)$. It suffices to show $\left(\beta^{*}-\right.$ $(\mathcal{P} \mathcal{H})^{\dagger} \bar{\mu}^{*})^{\top} \mu^{*}(\theta)=\hat{p}^{*}(\theta)$. The cases of $I_{<}=\emptyset$ or $I_{=}=\emptyset$ can be handled easily. We assume both of them are nonempty. Also let $I_{=}=[k]$, and $I_{<}=[k+1, \ldots, n]$ without loss of generality. The finite inverse moment assumption on bidgap implies $\nabla^{2} \mathbb{E}\left[f\left(\theta, \beta^{*}\right)\right] \beta^{*}=0$, and $\mathcal{H}=\operatorname{diag}\left(b_{i} /\left(\beta_{i}^{*}\right)^{2}\right)$. So $\beta^{*}=\left[1_{k} ; \beta_{<}^{*}\right]$ where $\beta_{<}^{*}$ is the

subvector corresponding to $I_{<}$. Let $\mathcal{H}_{<}$be the lower-right matrix of $\mathcal{H}$ corresponding to $I_{<}$. Lemma 1, Eq. (17) and $\nabla^{2} \mathbb{E}\left[f\left(\theta, \beta^{*}\right)\right] \beta^{*}=0$ imply $(\mathcal{P H P})^{t} \bar{\mu}^{*}=\left[0_{k} ; \beta_{<}^{*}\right]$. So $\beta^{*}-(\mathcal{P H P})^{t} \bar{\mu}^{*}=\left[1_{k} ; 0_{n-k}\right]$. And $\left[1_{k} ; 0_{n-k}\right]^{\top} \mu^{*}(\theta)=$ $\sum_{i \in I_{=}} \mu_{i}^{*}(\theta)=\bar{p}^{*}$. The simplified formula for $\Sigma_{\beta}$ follows easily.

Next we show $\hat{\sigma}_{\mathrm{REV}, \text { sim }}^{2} \xrightarrow{p} \sigma_{\mathrm{REV}}^{2}$. Suppose $I_{=}=\emptyset$, then $\mathbb{P}\left(\hat{I}_{=}=I_{=}\right) \rightarrow 1$ implies $\hat{\sigma}_{\mathrm{REV}}^{2} \rightarrow 0$. Now suppose $I_{=} \neq \emptyset$. In Lemma EC. 22 we have shown both $\mathcal{F}_{1}$ and $\mathcal{F}_{3}$ are VC-subgraph, and thus a uniform law of large number holds. Since $\mathbb{P}\left(\hat{I}_{=}=I_{=}\right) \rightarrow 1$, we analysis is carried out under the event $\hat{I}_{=}=I_{=}$. Let $f(\theta, \beta)$ be the function in $\mathcal{F}_{1}$ and $g$ in $\mathcal{F}_{3}$. Let $h(\theta, \beta)=f(\theta, \beta) g(\theta, \beta)$. Under the event $\hat{I}_{=}=I_{=}$, we have that $\hat{\sigma}_{\mathrm{REV}}^{2}$ is the sample variance of $h\left(\theta^{\tau}, \beta^{\gamma}\right), \tau \in[t]$, and $\hat{\sigma}_{\mathrm{REV}}^{2}$ is the variance of the random variable $h\left(\theta, \beta^{*}\right)$. The consistency of the simplified revenue variance estimator follows by the uniform law of large number. The consistency of the simplified estimator for $\Sigma_{\beta}$ follows easily. Q.E.D.

# G.10. Proof of Theorem 14 

Proof of Theorem 14 By the EG characterization of FPPE, we know that $\beta^{\gamma}(1)$, the pacing multiplier of the observed $\operatorname{FPPE} \widehat{\operatorname{FPPE}}(\pi b, v(1), \frac{\pi}{t_{1}}, \gamma(1))$, solves the following dual EG program

$$
\min _{B} \frac{1}{t_{1}} \sum_{\tau=1}^{t_{1}} \max _{i} v_{i}\left(\theta^{\tau}\right) \beta_{i}-\sum_{i=1}^{n} b_{i} \log \left(\beta_{i}\right)
$$

The major technical challenge is that the number of summands in the first summation is also random. Given a fixed integer $k$ and a sequence of items $\left(\theta^{1,1}, \ldots, \theta^{1, k}\right)$, define

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \beta^{\operatorname{lin}, k}(1)=\beta^{*}(1)+\frac{1}{k} \sum_{\tau=1}^{k} D_{\beta}\left(1, \theta^{1, \tau}\right) \\
& \beta^{k}(1)=\text { the unique pacing multiplier in } \widehat{\operatorname{FPPE}}\left(b, v(1), k^{-1},\left(\theta^{1,1}, \ldots, \theta^{1, k}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Here $D_{\beta}(1, \cdot)=-\left(\mathcal{H}_{B}(1)\right)^{t}\left(\mu^{*}(1, \cdot)-\bar{\mu}^{*}(1)\right)$ where $\mathcal{H}_{B}(1), \mu^{*}(1, \cdot)$ and $\bar{\mu}^{*}(1)$ are the projected Hessian in Eq. (18), item utility function in Eq. (15), and total item utility vector in Eq. (16) in the limit market $\operatorname{FPPE}(b, v(1), s)$. Note $\mathbb{E}\left[D_{\beta}(1, \cdot)\right]=0$. Note $\beta^{\gamma}(1)=\beta^{t_{1}}$ since scaling the supply and the budget at the same time does not change the equilibrium pacing multiplier. We introduce the following asymptotic equivalence results:

Lemma EC.24. Recall $t_{1} \sim \operatorname{Bin}(\pi, t)$. If Assumption 2 and Assumption 1 hold for the limit market $\operatorname{FPPE}(b, v(1), s)$, then

- $\sqrt{t}\left(\beta^{\gamma}(1)-\beta^{\text {lin }, t_{1}}\right)=o_{p}(1)$ as $t \rightarrow \infty$.
- $\sqrt{t}\left(\beta^{\text {lin }, t_{1}}-\beta^{\text {lin },\lfloor\pi t\rfloor}\right)=o_{p}(1)$ as $t \rightarrow \infty$.

Here $\lfloor a\rfloor$ is the greatest integer less than or equal to $a \in \mathbb{R}$. A similar result holds for the market limit $\operatorname{FPPE}(b, v(0), s)$ and the influence function $D_{\beta}(0, \cdot)$ is defined similarly.

With Lemma EC.24, we write

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sqrt{t}\left(\bar{\tau}_{\beta}-\tau_{\beta}\right) \\
& =\sqrt{t}\left(\beta^{\gamma}(1)-\beta^{*}(1)\right)-\sqrt{t}\left(\beta^{\gamma}(0)-\beta^{*}(0)\right) \\
& =\sqrt{t}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{\lfloor\pi t\rfloor}} \sum_{\tau=1}^{\lfloor\pi t\rfloor} D_{\beta}\left(1, \theta^{1, \tau}\right)-\frac{1}{\sqrt{\lfloor(1-\pi) t\rfloor}} \sum_{\tau=1}^{\lfloor(1-\pi) t\rfloor} D_{\beta}\left(0, \theta^{0, \tau}\right)\right)+o_{p}(1) \\
& \xrightarrow{d} \mathcal{N}\left(0, \frac{1}{\pi} \operatorname{Var}\left[D_{\beta}(1, \cdot)\right]+\frac{1}{(1-\pi)} \operatorname{Var}\left[D_{\beta}(0, \cdot)\right]\right) . \quad \text { (independence between }\left\{\theta^{1, \tau}\right\}_{\tau} \text { and }\left\{\theta^{0, \tau}\right\}_{\tau}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Proof of CLT for $\tau_{\beta}$. It follows from the above discussion.
Proof of CLT for $\tau_{u}$. We begin with the linear expansion Eq. (EC.43) and repeat the same argument.
Proof of CLT for $\tau_{\mathrm{REV}}$. We begin with the linear expansion Eq. (EC.41) and repeat the same argument.
Proof of CLT for $\tau_{\mathrm{NSW}}$. We begin with the linear expansion Eq. (EC.44) and repeat the same argument.
We complete the proof of Theorem 14. Q.E.D.
In order to prove Lemma EC. 24 , we will need the following lemma.

Lemma EC.25. If $X_{t}=o_{p}(1)$ and $T \sim \operatorname{Bin}(\pi, t)$ and $T$ and the sequence are independent, then $X_{T}=o_{p}(1)$.

Proof of Lemma EC. 25 By $X_{t}=o_{p}(1)$ we know for all $\epsilon>0$ it holds $\mathbb{P}\left(\left|X_{t}\right|>\epsilon\right) \rightarrow 0$, or equivalently $\sup _{k \geq t} \mathbb{P}\left(\left|X_{k}\right|>\epsilon\right) \rightarrow 0$ as $t \rightarrow \infty$. By a concentration for binomial distribution, we know for all $\delta>0$, it holds $\mathbb{P}(|T-\pi t|>\delta \pi t) \leq 2 \exp \left(-\delta^{2} \pi t / 3\right)$. Now write

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}\left(\left|X_{T}\right|>\epsilon\right) & \leq \mathbb{P}\left(\left|X_{T}\right|>\epsilon, T \in(1 \pm \delta) \pi t\right)+\mathbb{P}(T \notin(1 \pm \delta) \pi t) \\
& \leq \sum_{k \in(1 \pm \delta) \pi t} \mathbb{P}\left(\left|X_{k}\right|>\epsilon\right) \mathbb{P}(T=k)+2 \exp \left(-\delta^{2} \pi t / 3\right) \\
& \leq \sup _{k \geq(1-\delta) \pi t} \mathbb{P}\left(\left|X_{k}\right|>\epsilon\right)+2 \exp \left(-\delta^{2} \pi t / 3\right) \rightarrow 0 \text { as } t \rightarrow \infty
\end{aligned}
$$

where in the second inequality we use the independence between $T$ and the sequence. We conclude $X_{T}=o_{p}(1)$, completing proof of Lemma EC.25. Q.E.D.

Proof of Lemma EC. 24 The first statement uses the independence between $t_{1}$ and the items $\left(\theta^{1,1}, \theta^{1,2}, \ldots\right)$. Define $R(k)=\sqrt{t}\left(\beta^{k}(1)-\beta^{\operatorname{lin}, k}(1)\right)$. By Eq. (EC.39), we have $R(k)=o_{p}(1)$ as $k \rightarrow \infty$. With this notation, the first statement is equivalent to $R\left(t_{1}\right)=o_{p}(1)$ where $t_{1} \sim \operatorname{Bin}(\pi, t)$, which holds true by Lemma EC. 25 .

The second statement is equivalent to $\sqrt{[\pi t]}\left(\beta^{\operatorname{lin}, t_{1}}(1)-\beta^{\operatorname{lin},\lfloor\pi t\rfloor}(1)\right)=o_{p}(1)$. To prove this we use a Komogorov's inequality. By Theorem 2.5.5 from Durrett (2019), for any $\epsilon>0$, (let $\sigma_{D_{\beta}}=\mathbb{E}\left[\left\|D_{\beta}(1, \theta)\right\|_{21}^{21 / 1 / 2}\right)$

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\sqrt{[\pi t]} \sup _{(1-\epsilon) \lfloor\pi t\rfloor \leq m \leq(1+\epsilon) \lfloor\pi t\rfloor}\left\|\beta^{\operatorname{lin}, m}(1)-\beta^{\operatorname{lin},(1-\epsilon) \lfloor\pi t\rfloor}(1)\right\|_{2} \geq \delta \sigma_{D_{\beta}}\right) \leq \frac{2 \epsilon}{\delta^{2}}
$$

Then

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{P}\left(\sqrt{[\pi t]}\left\|\beta^{\operatorname{lin}, t_{1}}(1)-\beta^{\operatorname{lin},\lfloor\pi t\rfloor}(1)\right\|_{2} \geq \delta\right) \\
& \leq \mathbb{P}\left(\sqrt{[\pi t]}\left\|\beta^{\operatorname{lin}, t_{1}}(1)-\beta^{\operatorname{lin},\lfloor\pi t\rfloor}(1)\right\|_{2} \geq \delta,(1-\epsilon)\lfloor\pi t\rfloor \leq t_{1} \leq(1+\epsilon)\lfloor\pi t\rfloor\right) \\
& \quad+\mathbb{P}\left(t_{1} \notin[(1-\epsilon)\lfloor\pi t\rfloor,(1+\epsilon)\lfloor\pi t\rfloor]\right) \\
& \leq \frac{2 \epsilon \sigma_{D_{\beta}}^{2}}{\delta^{2}}+\mathbb{P}\left(t_{1} \notin[(1-\epsilon)\lfloor\pi t\rfloor,(1+\epsilon)\lfloor\pi t\rfloor]\right) \rightarrow \frac{2 \epsilon \sigma_{D_{\beta}}^{2}}{\delta^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally, since the above holds for all $\epsilon>0$, we obtain $\sqrt{[\pi t]}\left(\beta^{\operatorname{lin}, t_{1}}-\beta^{\operatorname{lin},\lfloor\pi t\rfloor}\right)=o_{p}(1)$. We complete the proof of Lemma EC.24. Q.E.D.

# Appendix H: Experiments
## H.1. Hessian Estimation

Setup. We look at the following configuration of markets and the smoothing parameter $d$. Note we will be evaluating Hessian at a prespecified point and do not need to form any market equilibria in this experiment. We consider $n=9$ buyers. The item size $t$ ranges from 200 to 5000 , at a log scale. Budget does not need to be specified. Buyers' values are drawn from uniform, exponential, or truncated standard normal distributions. The smoothing parameter $d$ is chosen from the grid $[0.10,0.17,0.25,0.32,0.40,0.47,0.55,0.62,0.70]$. We evaluate the Hessian $\nabla^{2} H$ at a pre-specified point $\beta=[0.200,0.333,0.467,0.600,0.733,0.867,1.000]$, and plot the estimated diagonal values, $\hat{\mathcal{H}}_{i i}$ for $i \in[7]$, against the number of items $t$. Under each configuration we repeat for 10 trials.

Results. See Figures EC. 3 to EC.5. We see that $d$ represents a bias-variance trade-off. For a small $d(0.10$, $0.17,0.25)$, the variance of the estimated value $\hat{\mathcal{H}}_{i i}$ is small and yet bias is large (since the plots seem to be trending to some point as number of item increases). For a large $d(0.55,0.62,0.70)$ variance is large and yet the bias is small (the estimates are stationary around some point). It is suggested to use $d \in(0.32,0.47)$.

abstract:
We initiate the study of statistical inference and A/B testing for two market
equilibrium models: linear Fisher market (LFM) equilibrium and first-price
pacing equilibrium (FPPE). LFM arises from fair resource allocation systems
such as allocation of food to food banks and notification opportunities to
different types of notifications. For LFM, we assume that the data observed is
captured by the classical finite-dimensional Fisher market equilibrium, and its
steady-state behavior is modeled by a continuous limit Fisher market. The
second type of equilibrium we study, FPPE, arises from internet advertising
where advertisers are constrained by budgets and advertising opportunities are
sold via first-price auctions. For platforms that use pacing-based methods to
smooth out the spending of advertisers, FPPE provides a hindsight-optimal
configuration of the pacing method. We propose a statistical framework for the
FPPE model, in which a continuous limit FPPE models the steady-state behavior
of the auction platform, and a finite FPPE provides the data to estimate
primitives of the limit FPPE. Both LFM and FPPE have an Eisenberg-Gale convex
program characterization, the pillar upon which we derive our statistical
theory. We start by deriving basic convergence results for the finite market to
the limit market. We then derive asymptotic distributions, and construct
confidence intervals. Furthermore, we establish the asymptotic local minimax
optimality of estimation based on finite markets. We then show that the theory
can be used for conducting statistically valid A/B testing on auction
platforms. Synthetic and semi-synthetic experiments verify the validity and
practicality of our theory.
